%N A390762 Number of ways to write n as (p-1)^2 + (q-1)^2 + (r-1)^2/2 + (s-1)^2/4 with p <= q, where each of p,q,r,s is either 1 or an odd prime.
%C A390762 Conjecture: Let S = {(p-1)/2: p is 1 or an odd prime}. Then each nonnegative integer n can be written as w^2 + b*x^2 + c*y^2 + d*z^2 with w,x,y,z in the set S, provided that (b,c,d) is among the following 25 triples: (1,2,3),(1,2,4),(1,2,5),(1,2,6),(1,2,7),(1,2,12),(1,3,5),(1,3,6),(2,2,3),(2,2,5),(2,3,3),(2,3,4),(2,3,5),(2,3,7),(2,3,9),(2,3,10),(2,4,4),(2,4,5),(2,4,9),(2,4,10),(2,4,11),(2,4,12),(2,5,7),(2,5,8),(2,5,9).
%C A390762 This conjecture holds for (b,c,d) = (2,4,4) if and only if a(n) > 0 for all n >= 0. We have verified a(n) > 0 for all n <= 10^6. It seems that a(n) = 1 only for n = 0, 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 14, 15, 30, 120, 130, 754, 770, 1186, 2290.
%D A390762 S. Ramanujan, On the expression of a number in the form a*x^2 + b*y^2 + c*z^2 + d*w^2, Proc. Cambridge Philos. Soc. 19 (1917), 11-21.
%H A390762 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A390762/b390762.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
